================================================================================
MBRPATCH  --  MBR partition table viewer and editor
Part of the mbr88 project: https://github.com/cpiker/mbr88
MIT License  Copyright (c) 2025 Chris Piker
================================================================================

DESCRIPTION

  mbrpatch reads, displays, and interactively edits the 512-byte Master
  Boot Record of an IBM XT-class hard disk image.  It understands the
  standard four-entry MBR partition table and the extended boot menu label
  feature of the mbr88 boot record.

  It can also read the MBR directly from a physical disk or write a
  prepared MBR image back to disk, removing the need for out-of-band tools
  like DEBUG.

  Changes to image files are always held in memory until you confirm a
  write with the 'w' command.  A backup copy (mbr_file.bak) is written
  before the file is changed.  Pressing 'q' before confirming a write
  leaves the file completely untouched.

  Device writes (-w) are permanent and have no automatic backup.  Always
  run mbrpatch -r first to save a copy of the existing MBR.

================================================================================
USAGE
================================================================================

  mbrpatch  <file>               View partition table of image file (read-only)
  mbrpatch  -p  <file>           Patch an existing MBR image interactively
  mbrpatch  -u  <file>           Upgrade existing MBR image to mbr88, then edit
  mbrpatch  -n  <file>           Create a new blank mbr88 image, then edit
  mbrpatch  -r  <file> <drive>   Read MBR from physical disk to image file
  mbrpatch  -w  <file> <drive>   Write MBR image file to physical disk
  mbrpatch  -h                   Print a short usage summary

  <drive> is the BIOS drive number:
    80h  =  first hard disk  (most common)
    81h  =  second hard disk

================================================================================
MODES
================================================================================

  (no flag) -- VIEW MODE (read-only)

    Reads the image file, checks that it is exactly 512 bytes and has a
    valid 55 AA boot signature, prints the partition table, and exits.
    The file is never modified.  Exits with an error if the file does not
    exist, is not 512 bytes, or lacks the 55 AA signature.

  -p -- PATCH MODE

    Validates the file the same way as view mode, then opens an interactive
    session for editing partitions.  If the file contains an mbr88 v0.1
    boot record, boot menu label editing is also available.  A higher mbr88
    version causes a message directing you to get a newer mbrpatch.

  -u -- UPGRADE MODE

    Validates the file, replaces its boot code with the mbr88 v0.1 boot
    record, and preserves the existing partition table entries.  The file
    MUST already exist.  Use -n to create a new image from scratch.
    After the upgrade, the session starts with unsaved changes flagged so
    the 'w' command will immediately offer to write the upgraded boot code.

  -n -- NEW MODE

    Creates a blank mbr88 v0.1 image and opens the interactive session.
    The target file MUST NOT already exist.  The program exits with an
    error if it does, preventing accidental overwrites.

  -r -- READ DISK MODE

    Reads the first sector (512 bytes) of the specified BIOS drive and
    saves it to the output file.  The partition table is displayed before
    saving.  The output file must not already exist (safety check).

    Use this before editing or upgrading an MBR to create a backup:

      mbrpatch -r original.bin 80h

  -w -- WRITE DISK MODE

    Loads the specified MBR image file, validates it, displays the
    partition table, and asks for confirmation before writing the 512
    bytes to the first sector of the specified BIOS drive.

    THIS OPERATION IS PERMANENT.  There is no automatic backup.  Always
    run -r first.  Wrong drive numbers may overwrite the wrong disk.

      mbrpatch -w mbr.bin 80h

================================================================================
INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
================================================================================

  g   Set drive geometry (heads per cylinder and sectors per track).
      Must be run before 'n'.  IBM XT default: 16 heads, 17 sectors.

  n   Define a new partition or redefine an existing one.
      Requires geometry to have been set with 'g' first.  Prompts for
      starting CHS, ending CHS, partition type, and bootable flag.
      LBA start and size are computed from the CHS values.

  d   Delete a partition slot.  Zeros all 16 bytes of the entry and its
      boot menu label.

  t   Change the partition type byte of an existing entry.
      Enter the type as hex without a leading prefix (e.g. type 06
      for FAT16B).  Any value 00-FF is accepted; types not in the
      built-in list display as "Unknown" in the partition summary.

  b   Toggle the bootable flag (inactive / bootable).
      mbr88 only shows bootable partitions in the boot menu.
      Unlike most MBR loaders, mbr88 allows more than one partition
      to be bootable at once -- all such partitions appear in the menu.

  v   Set the boot menu volume label for a partition (mbr88 v0.1 only).
      Up to 11 characters.  Shown in the boot menu next to the
      partition number.

  p   Print the current partition table.

  l   List common partition type codes.

  w   Ask for confirmation, write a backup copy to mbr_file.bak,
      then write the changes to the file.

  h   Print a short command summary.

  q   Quit.  Prompts if there are unsaved changes.

================================================================================
PARTITION TYPE CODES (common values)
================================================================================

  00  Empty              0B  FAT32
  01  FAT12              0C  FAT32 LBA
  02  Xenix root         0E  FAT16 LBA
  03  Xenix usr          0F  Extended LBA
  04  FAT16 <32MB        11  Hidden FAT12
  05  Extended           14  Hidden FAT16 <32MB
  06  FAT16B >=32MB      16  Hidden FAT16B
  07  HPFS/NTFS          1B  Hidden FAT32
  0A  OS/2 Boot Mgr      1C  Hidden FAT32 LBA
  64  NetWare 286        1E  Hidden FAT16 LBA
  80  MINIX orig/ELKS    81  MINIX
  82  Linux swap         83  Linux
  DB  CP/M-86

  Any value 00-FF is accepted.  Types not listed above display as
  "Unknown" in the partition summary.

================================================================================
EXAMPLES
================================================================================

  Save the current MBR from the first hard disk before making any changes:

    mbrpatch -r original.bin 80h

  View the saved image without modifying it:

    mbrpatch original.bin

  Upgrade the MBR to mbr88, set labels, and write the image file:

    mbrpatch -u original.bin

    At the prompt:
      g    (set geometry -- accept XT default or enter your values)
      b    (mark each bootable partition)
      v    (set a volume label, repeat for each partition)
      w    (write the upgraded boot code back to the file)

  Write the finished image to the hard disk (permanent -- no undo):

    mbrpatch -w original.bin 80h

  Create a fresh mbr88 image from scratch:

    mbrpatch -n new.bin

    At the prompt:
      g    (set geometry)
      n    (define partition 1, repeat for each partition)
      b    (mark bootable partitions)
      v    (set volume labels)
      w    (write the new image to new.bin)

    Then write it to disk:
      mbrpatch -w new.bin 80h

================================================================================
MBR88 BOOT RECORD
================================================================================

  mbr88 is a custom MBR for IBM XT-class hardware.  It presents a boot menu
  and always waits for the user to choose what to boot.  The menu supports
  hard disk partitions 1-4 and floppy drives A and B.

  Only bootable partitions appear in the menu.  mbr88 allows more than one
  partition to be bootable at once -- use the 'b' command in mbrpatch to
  set the flag on each partition you want selectable.  Conventional tools
  like FDISK enforce a single active partition; after running FDISK you
  will need to re-run mbrpatch to restore the flags on additional boot
  partitions.

  The mbr88 boot record retries disk reads up to three times before
  reporting an error, which allows floppy drive motors time to reach
  stable speed.

  mbr88 is identified by the signature 'mbr88' at MBR offset 0x1B8,
  followed by a version byte at 0x1BD.  Version 01 = v0.1.

  Boot menu labels are stored at MBR offset 0x41 in four 16-byte slots.
  Each slot holds up to 11 characters displayed next to the partition
  number in the boot menu.  Labels are only editable on mbr88 v0.1
  images.  If a newer mbr88 version is found, get an updated mbrpatch:

    https://github.com/cpiker/mbr88

================================================================================
NOTES
================================================================================

  Drive numbers: BIOS hard disk numbers start at 80h.  80h is always the
  first hard disk.  81h is the second.  Drive letters under DOS may be
  remapped (for example by EtherDFS or network redirectors), so drive
  letters are not used here.  Always use the BIOS number.

  Drive geometry: IBM XT hard disks typically use 16 heads and 17 sectors
  per track.  The geometry entered with 'g' must match the values used
  when the partitions were originally created, or the computed LBA fields
  will be wrong.  XT-class BIOSes use only the CHS fields and ignore LBA,
  so wrong LBA values rarely cause problems in practice.

  CHS values should be taken from fdisk or the drive's technical
  specification.

================================================================================
FILES
================================================================================

  mbr_file.bak    Backup of the image file, written before any file write.
                  No automatic backup is made for device writes (-w).

